<dl id="n32051b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n32" href="#n32051b">N32 (VI.B.23)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n32all.htm#n32051b"> 51(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> lahnnda n / At 74&deg; degree / transition dialect</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Taking the tract covered by these three forms of speech, it has to its west, in the western Punjab, <mark>Lahnda</mark>, a language of the outer band. The parent of Lahnda once no doubt covered the whole of the Punjab, but, in the process of expansion of the tribes of the Midland &hellip;, it was gradually driven back, leaving traces of its former existence which grow stronger as we proceed westwards, until <mark>at about the 74th degree of east longitude there is a mixed, transition dialect</mark>. <small> &ldquo;HINDOSTANI&rdquo; <a name="EBHI" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#EBHI"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) 479(a) [Linguistic boundaries]</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
